 for bestpractices and # Dashboard

## Overview
Create a role-aware, enterprise-grade dashboard as the primary landing page after login. It should present active audits, quick-action shortcuts, key metrics, and a recent activity feed. Content and available actions must adapt to user roles (reviewer, admin, field user). The UI must be data-driven, performant, accessible, and safe against null/undefined values in all data paths. The feature will be consumed by an AI development tool to generate frontend components, backend endpoints, and integration glue, following the project’s design system and runtime safety requirements.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- The Dashboard is the central hub for authenticated users, presenting a concise, at-a-glance view of critical audit operations. It aggregates active audits, recent events, and quick actions to accelerate field work and review tasks.

Goals:
- Provide immediate visibility into audits in flight, items detected today, pending reviews, and utilization of export credits.
- Streamline workflows with quick actions: Start Capture, Upload Batch, Open Review Queue, Create Audit.
- Show role-aware content: reviewers see pending reviews and review-centric actions; admins see audit creation and export controls; field users see capture and site-level progress.
- Ensure secure, tenant-isolated data access with robust validation and error handling.
- Maintain a clean, card-based UI with intuitive navigation, consistent spacing, and responsive behavior.

Features connected:
- Active audits list with filters by site/location and status
- Quick actions toolbar
- KPI/summary panels
- Recent activity feed (audit changes, uploads, reviews, status updates)
- Sites overview with per-site metrics and CTAs
- Role-based content gating and piecewise enabling/disabling of actions

UI elements and how they should look:
- Top Navigation: Global search, tenant/site selector, user avatar with dropdown (profile, settings, logout)
- KPI Panels: Four stat cards (Active Audits, Items Detected Today, Pending Reviews, Export Credits Used) arranged in a responsive grid
- Quick Actions: Pill-shaped buttons (Start Capture, Upload Batch, Open Review Queue, Create Audit) with lime-green accent for primary actions
- Activity Feed: Timeline-style list with icons, timestamps, and succinct descriptions
- Sites Overview: Card list of sites with metrics and an “Open Site” CTA per card
- Role-aware content: Visible actions and panels adjust based on role; some panels may show read-only summaries for non-privileged roles
- Visual guidance: High-contrast, with the specified color palette and typographic scale

API integrations:
- No external API connections required for this task, but the frontend must be designed to consume a hypothetical API shape (supplied via project context) with robust guards for data absent or null.

## Components to Build
- DashboardShell
  - Layout container with top navigation, left sidebar (icon stack), and main content region
- KPIPanel
  - Reusable card displaying title, value, delta/status, and an optional small trend indicator
- ActiveAuditsGrid
  - List or grid of current audits with status chips, site, last updated, and actions
- QuickActionsBar
  - Row or grid of action buttons: Start Capture, Upload Batch, Open Review Queue, Create Audit
- RecentActivityFeed
  - Timeline-style feed with items: audit changes, uploads, reviews; includes timestamp and brief description
- SitesOverview
  - Card-based listing of sites with site-level metrics and an Open Site CTA
- RoleGuard
  - Lightweight utility to conditionally render components based on user role
- AvatarMenu
  - User avatar with dropdown actions
- DataCard
  - Generic card used for section blocks with title, metadata, and content
- EmptyState
  - Reusable empty-state component for pages with no data
- Utility Hooks
  - useFetchDashboardData (mocked/placeholder for data wiring in AI tool)
  - useUserRole
  - useSupaSafeData helper (null/undefined guards as per runtime safety)

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Frameworks: React (with TypeScript) or a comparable modern stack per project conventions
- State management: useState/useEffect with proper initialization; consider lightweight context or props drilling for this isolated task
- Styling: Inline CSS-in-JS or CSS Modules matching the design system; ensure color tokens map to the Visual Style; responsive layout with grid/flex
- Accessibility: ARIA roles, keyboard navigation, sufficient color contrast per palette
- Data handling safety (CRITICAL):
  - Initialize arrays with proper defaults: useState<T[]>([]) for all array data
  - Guard all data accesses: const audits = data?.audits ?? [] or Array.isArray(data?.audits) ? data.audits : []
  - Use data ?? [] when handling Supabase results
  - Validate API shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
  - Optional chaining for nested objects: item?.field?.subfield
  - Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}
- UI behavior:
  - KPI values should gracefully render zero or placeholder if data is missing
  - Quick actions should be enabled/disabled based on user role
  - Active audits should show a default “No active audits” state if empty
- Data visualization:
  - Even if charts are not rendered, provide card-ready data props for mini-charts or sparklines
  - Use status chips with color tokens from the palette
- Routing and navigation:
  - Dashboard route path as /dashboard
  - Links or CTAs should navigate to pages like /audits, /reviews, /sites, /capture
- API integration scaffolding:
  - Define types for API responses (DashboardData, Audit, Site, Activity)
  - Use placeholders for API calls with mocks or deterministic shapes
- Performance considerations:
  - Debounce or throttle global search if implemented
  - Lazy-load sections if data is heavy (the prompt requires a self-contained build, but plan for async data)
- Testing aids:
  - Prop-driven components with clear default props
  - Unit-testable pure functions for data shaping (even if tests are not written here)

### Backend
- APIs (if implemented in the tool’s scope):
  - Endpoints to fetch dashboard data (GET /api/dashboard) returning:
    - audits: Audit[]
    - kpis: { activeAudits: number, itemsToday: number, pendingReviews: number, exportCreditsUsed: number }
    - recentActivities: Activity[]
    - sites: Site[]
  - Endpoints to trigger quick actions (startCapture, uploadBatch, createAudit, openReviewQueue)
- Data model considerations:
  - Audits linked to tenant, site, and user
  - Sites with metrics
  - Activities with timestamps and type
- Validation and sanitation:
  - Validate all incoming data; guard against missing fields
  - Enforce role-based data exposure at the API layer if applicable

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - DashboardData fetched on mount; stored in local state with appropriate guards
  - RoleGuard wraps sections to present role-appropriate UI
  - Quick actions call corresponding endpoints or route to relevant pages
  - RecentActivity and SitesOverview render from same dataset structures
- Data synchronization:
  - After quick actions, optimistically reflect immediate UI changes or trigger refetch
- Consistency:
  - Use consistent date/time formatting and relative timestamps
  - Align card titles, metadata, and CTAs with design system tokens

## User Experience Flow
1. User logs in and lands on Dashboard at /dashboard
2. Dashboard loads: top navigation shows tenant/site and user avatar
3. KPI panels render with data (fallback to placeholders if none)
4. Quick Actions bar presents enabled actions per role
5. Active Audits grid shows current audits; each card reveals status and quick actions
6. Recent Activity feed lists latest events (audit changes, uploads, reviews)
7. Sites Overview cards present per-site metrics and an Open Site CTA
8. User interacts with a Quick Action:
   - Start Capture routes to capture flow
   - Upload Batch opens batch upload modal or page
   - Open Review Queue navigates to reviews
   - Create Audit opens audit creation flow
9. User may open a site or audit to drill down; data remains consistent with role-based visibility

## Technical Specifications
- Data Models:
  - Audit: { id, siteId, status, lastUpdated, ownerId, itemsDetected, etc. }
  - Site: { id, name, location, metrics: { activeAudits, itemsToday, pendingReviews } }
  - Activity: { id, type, timestamp, description, auditId, siteId, userId }
  - User: { id, role, name, avatarUrl, tenantId }
- API Endpoints:
  - GET /api/dashboard -> DashboardData
  - POST /api/audits/startCapture
  - POST /api/audits/uploadBatch
  - POST /api/audits/create
  - GET /api/audits/reviewQueue
  - GET /api/sites
- Security:
  - JWT or SSO-ready auth; role-based access checks
  - Tenant isolation in data fetches; ensure no cross-tenant data leakage
  - Input validation on all mutation endpoints
- Validation:
  - Always validate response shapes; use Array.isArray checks; fallback to [] if missing
  - Use nullish coalescing for arrays from APIs: const items = data ?? []
- Accessibility:
  - All interactive elements keyboard accessible
  - Voiceover-friendly markup for screen readers

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Dashboard renders with four KPI panels updating from a robust DashboardData shape; handles null/undefined gracefully
- [ ] Active Audits grid handles empty state and role-based visibility; all data guarded against nulls
- [ ] Quick Actions are enabled/disabled per role and trigger the correct navigations or API calls
- [ ] Recent Activity feed displays latest events; timestamps formatted; data guarded against missing fields
- [ ] Sites Overview shows per-site metrics; Open Site CTA navigates to /sites/{id}
- [ ] All array data are initialized as empty arrays; no direct .map/.filter/.reduce on potentially null values
- [ ] All API response shapes validated; fallback to empty arrays/zero values
- [ ] UI adheres to the provided color palette, typography, spacing, and card styling guidelines

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
---
## Visual Style

### Color Palette:
- Primary background: Soft light gray (#F5F6F8) for main workspace, with slightly darker gray (#E8E9EC) for card backgrounds
- Accent color: Vibrant lime green (#C9FF52) for highlighting key actions, events, and active states
- Secondary colors: Pure white (#FFFFFF) for card and modal surfaces, deep black (#18191A) for navigation and summary panels, and mid-gray (#B6B7BA) for dividers and muted text
- Text: Dark gray (#232323) for primary text, lighter gray (#6B6B6B) for secondary text, and white (#FFFFFF) on dark backgrounds
- Additional accents: Red (#FF5E5E) for warning or error states, orange (#FFC85E) and sky blue (#6ECFFF) for secondary status and tags
- Color relationships: High contrast between accent green and muted neutrals for clear focus; black panels create visual anchor points

### Typography & Layout:
- Font family: Clean, geometric sans-serif (e.g., Inter, SF Pro, or Circular)
- Font weights: Regular for body, bold for headings, medium for labels and CTAs
- Hierarchy: Large, bold headings; medium-weight subheads; lighter secondary labels and metadata
- Spacing: Generous padding and margin between cards and sections (24–32px), with consistent vertical rhythm
- Alignment: Left-aligned text, center-aligned key metrics, and edge-to-edge card layouts
- Treatments: Subtle use of color and weight for emphasis; iconography paired with text for clarity

### Key Design Elements

#### Card Design:
- Card styling: Rounded corners (16–24px radius), mild drop shadows for elevation, white or very light gray backgrounds
- Borders: Minimal or none, relying on shadow and spacing for separation
- Hover/active: Subtle shadow intensification or light outline; accent green highlight for selected cards
- Visual hierarchy: Prominent title, secondary metadata, compact icons and tags at the bottom

#### Navigation:
- Top bar: Pill-shaped, black with white and accent green highlights for active items
- Sidebar: Minimal vertical icon stack, outlined with subtle dividers
- Active states: High-contrast color (green or white on black) and pill backgrounds for current section
- Collapsible/expandable: Not explicitly shown, but navigation elements are designed to support modular expansion

#### Data Visualization:
